 this period, criminal news and crime fiction flourished. Civil society’s search for truth and justice led, paradoxically, to the normalization of extrajudicial violence and neglect of the rights of victims. As Pablo Piccato demonstrates, ordinary people in Mexico have made crime and punishment central concerns of the public sphere during the last century, and in doing so have shaped crime and violence in our times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aCrime and the presszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aCrime writingxHistory and criticism. 0aCrimezMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aDetective and mystery stories, MexicanxHistory and criticism. 0aJustice, Administration ofzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh  a20th century.  acrime and punishment.  acrime fiction.  acrime.  acriminal investigation.  acriminal justice.  acriminal law.  acriminal.  adanger.  ahistory.  ajudicial system.  ajustice system.  ajustice.  alatin america.  amexican government.  amexican politics.  amexican.  amexico.  apolice system.  apolice.  apolicing.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apost revolution.  apublic sphere.  arevolution.  arevolutionary.  asafety.  asocial history.  atrue crime.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029262840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966079/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY